# Cyber Fidget firmware tests

## Where tests live

PlatformIO 6.x requires test directories under a single top-level
`test/` path — `test_dir` is a `[platformio]`-section option, not
per-environment. To keep app-owned tests visually separated from
core/infra tests while staying inside what pio supports, we use a
**naming convention** under `test/`:

```
cyberfidget-firmware/
└── test/
    ├── README                          ← this file
    ├── test_core_<thing>/              ← core / infra owned
    │   └── test_<thing>.cpp
    └── test_<appname>_<thing>/         ← app-owned
        └── test_<thing>.cpp
```

The `test_<scope>_` prefix unambiguously says who owns a test
directory. Per-env `test_filter = test_<scope>_*` in `platformio.ini`
scopes which directories run for each test environment.

> If we ever migrate to a layout where each app physically owns its
> own `lib/<App>/test/` directory, that's a PR against PlatformIO
> itself (or a switch to a custom test runner). The naming
> convention above is the best fit while we live under stock pio
> behavior. See `N-012` for the long-term scaling plan.

## Test environments

| Env                | Runs                     | Invoke |
|--------------------|--------------------------|--------|
| `test_core`        | `test/test_core_*/`       | `pio test -e test_core` |
| `test_breakout`    | `test/test_breakout_*/`   | `pio test -e test_breakout` |

To add a new app's tests:

1. Create `test/test_<yourapp>_<thing>/test_<thing>.cpp` under `test/`.
2. Add an `[env:test_<yourapp>]` block to `platformio.ini` with
   `test_filter = test_<yourapp>_*` and any `build_flags` /
   `lib_deps` your tests need.
3. Verify with `pio test -e test_<yourapp>`.

When the env count crosses ~5 or `platformio.ini` crosses 300 lines,
migrate to per-app `extra_configs` per **N-012** (planning repo).

## Running tests

```
pio test                       # everything
pio test -e test_core          # just core tests
pio test -e test_breakout      # just BreakoutGame tests
```

All test envs use `platform = native`: tests build with the host
compiler (GCC / Clang) and run as a regular executable. No device
flash, no Arduino runtime. Tests that need real hardware behavior
go through `pio test -e local` (embedded mode) or the WASM SIL
harness (T-002).

### Host compiler requirement

Native `pio test` needs a C / C++ compiler on PATH. On a fresh
Windows dev box you typically don't have one. Install one of:

- **MSYS2 / MinGW-w64** — `https://www.msys2.org/`, then
  `pacman -S mingw-w64-ucrt-x86_64-gcc`, add MinGW's `bin` to PATH.
- **LLVM/Clang for Windows** — `https://releases.llvm.org/`
- **Visual Studio Build Tools** with the C++ workload — biggest
  install, but pio understands `cl.exe` via `platform = native`.

On Linux / macOS or in Docker (`Dockerfile.build` once `build-essential`
or `g++` is added), the compiler is already present and `pio test`
just works.

CI runners (GHA `ubuntu-latest`, Jenkins on the Docker image) ship
with GCC out of the box, so these tests will pass in CI even when
they can't run on a Windows laptop without one of the installs above.

## What gets tested today

- `test/test_core_version/` — placeholder Unity smoke test verifying
  the test toolchain works. The bash layer
  `scripts/test_acceptance.sh` covers most version assertions today;
  this directory is the migration target as we move things into
  Unity.

- `test/test_breakout_paddle_math/` — paddle-deflection physics
  (`BreakoutMath::reflectFromPaddle`), including the deterministic
  textured perturbation that activates on level 6+.
- `test/test_breakout_level_table/` — `BreakoutMath::isLayoutRowValid`
  catches typos in level-layout strings before flashing.
- `test/test_breakout_input_mapping/` — **app↔HAL contract** tests
  using `lib/HALMock/` to drive HAL extern globals. Verifies slider
  range (0..100), accelerometer sign convention, paddle clamping.
  These catch the regression class "core silently changed slider
  range; how would we know?" — slider/accel range or sign changes
  break these tests immediately.

## What's NOT here yet

- Full BreakoutGame-instance integration tests (would need a
  complete HALMock that stubs DisplayProxy, AudioManager,
  ButtonManager, RGBController, MenuManager). Punted to **T-002**'s
  WASM SIL harness — same firmware binary running in a browser
  with plant models is a better fidelity-for-effort tradeoff than
  stubbing every Arduino dependency.

- Device-side embedded tests. The `[env:local]` build path
  supports `pio test -e local` if a test needs real silicon (real
  I2S, real NeoPixel timing, etc.), but no such tests are written
  yet.

